{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8177fc6a-1d1b-4803-bf39-91f80f5dba20","content":"**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Here are the results (.NET 10, 64-bit):\n\n```\nType: Span<System.IntPtr>    // nint is an alias for IntPtr\nLength: 4\nSum: 100\nsizeof(nint): 8\nnuint span sum: 300\n```\n\nKey notes:\n- `nint`/`nuint` are aliases for `IntPtr`/`UIntPtr`, which are valid unmanaged types, so `stackalloc` works fine.\n- You do need `<AllowUnsafeBlocks>true</AllowUnsafeBlocks>` in the project since `stackalloc` inside an `unsafe` block requires it (though assigning directly to a `Span<T>` in a safe context also works without `unsafe`).\n- `sizeof(nint)` is 8 on 64-bit and would be 4 on 32-bit — that's the \"native-sized\" part.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1c697fc5-c76a-483b-a4f6-9a1bb1bcfb17","outputTokens":252,"requestId":"0411:2AE020:4307F3:4E6EA3:69F00447"},"id":"202ffe90-48f4-45ac-a74c-cf5d143ba367","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:50:22.562Z","parentId":"3959761b-464e-462f-a31c-f6cae91de250"}
